tweet: @SMTuffy @CaseyNewton and then oops you are sending a substack newsletter outside of your job.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SMTuffy @CaseyNewton and if you have a big enough distribution, you might use some email service - mailchimp, etc. - to manage your list and send your emails. you might use substack, for instance, which i believe costs nothing if you send a free newsletter.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SMTuffy @CaseyNewton and because some people don't like getting, or sending, bare-bones "here are my recent articles" emails, sometimes these emails will start with a little personal update or voice or commentary or whatever.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SMTuffy @CaseyNewton this has always been a thing that media companies encourage, because they want their reporters to be in frequent touch with sources, and they want people to promote their articles.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SMTuffy @CaseyNewton a lot of reporters send periodic updates on their work to a distribution list consisting of, like, friends and family and colleagues but also *sources* and subjects; it's a courtesy and a distribution tool and a reporting tool.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SandrewFinance @pearkes like at some point you have a level of knowledge about the world that might rise to near-certainty, even to "beyond a reasonable doubt" certainty, *before* a jury has convicted. and there on your substack why not give your readers access to your knowledge about the world?

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SandrewFinance @pearkes but at some point you do journalism and acquire facts. like if there's video of the guy doing it, and you watch it, and you call the guy's lawyer and he says "yeah he did it," and you talk to witnesses who say "we saw him do it," what value is there in the magic word "allegedly"?

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SandrewFinance @pearkes well (1) is complicated. if the police say "we arrested a guy who did a murder and he confessed," the reporter on deadline should say "police say ____" (or "allegedly"); you should not take the police's word for it.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @pearkes @SandrewFinance also to get back to the original point i think that what value "allegedly" has is much higher in mainstream factual news reports than it is in bloggers' commentary about What It Means, etc.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @pearkes @SandrewFinance to be clear i don't have a particular problem with "allegedly," and use it, i just don't think it has that much value for (1) informing readers, (2) protecting the innocent-until-proven-guilty or (3) avoiding liability.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @pearkes @SandrewFinance in general i think the long-run goal for journalism should be to try your best to describe the world accurately. that should *not* be the standard for criminal justice, which really should try hard to err on the side of under-punishing. (not that it always does, but.)

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @pearkes @SandrewFinance but i also think that if they do have the wrong guy or whatever, wall-to-wall coverage saying "allegedly" doesn't help that guy much.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @pearkes @SandrewFinance the justice system quite properly has a lot of safeguards and stylization due to its awesome power and terrible effects. some guy on substack? idk.

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @pearkes @SandrewFinance i strongly strongly disagree with this, i think that the standard for putting a human in a cage should be much higher than the standard for a blogger to say "yeah i think oj probably did it."

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @mattyglesias gotta create a separate, higher subscription tier for the substack-drama posts

name: Matt Levine
tweet: @SandrewFinance i tend to think that the magic-amulet power of "allegedly" is generally overrated in media. if someone is widely reported to have confessed to murders, what, he's gonna sue some substackers for commenting?   (not legal advice etc.)
